:::summary
The Magna Carta ("Great Charter"), sealed by King John of England on June 15, 1215, was the first document to formally establish that the king was subject to the rule of law. Though written to protect the rights of medieval barons, its principles — that no man is above the law, that arbitrary imprisonment is forbidden, and that justice must not be sold or denied — became the foundation of constitutional government throughout the English-speaking world and beyond.
:::

